I"'<p>The <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/memory-is-like-a-manuscript">memory systems</a> of contemporary computers are location-based, meaning that <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/meshing-discretizes-continuous-spaces">discrete</a> <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/concept-handles-are-like-addresses">locations</a> in <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/memory-is-perception-of-structural-artifacts">memory</a> are queried using pointers. In contrast, the <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/brain-is-like-hardware-mind-is-like-software">neural networks</a> seem to use content-based memory, meaning that content <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/optimizing-for-short-semantic-distances-fosters-learning">similar</a> to the query is retrieved.</p>
